detailed_results.query: What are the key compliance dates for New Zealand startups?
detailed_results.response:
KEY COMPLIANCE DATES FOR NEW ZEALAND STARTUPS

1. REGULAR TAX PAYMENTS
   • Provisional Tax Payments:
     - 28 August 2025
     - 15 January 2026
     - 7 May 2026
   
2. ANNUAL REQUIREMENTS
   • Income Tax Returns: Due 7 April 2026
   
3. PERIODIC RETURNS
   • GST Returns:
     - For turnover <$500K: 6-monthly (due 5 September and 5 February)
     - For turnover $500K-$24M: 2-monthly
     - For turnover >$24M: Monthly
   • PAYE Returns: Monthly (if employing staff)

IMPORTANT NOTES:
• These dates assume a standard March 31 balance date
• Additional requirements may apply based on business structure
• All dates assume timely filing without extensions
• GST registration required if annual turnover exceeds $60,000

RECOMMENDATION:
Set up a compliance calendar with reminders at least one month before each due date to ensure timely preparation and submission.

detailed_results.query: What are the GST registration requirements for my startup?
detailed_results.response:
GST REGISTRATION REQUIREMENTS FOR NZ STARTUPS:

MANDATORY REGISTRATION:
• Required if your turnover exceeds or is expected to exceed NZ$60,000 in any 12-month period
• Applies to both goods and services sold in New Zealand

VOLUNTARY REGISTRATION:
• Businesses can register even if turnover is below $60,000
• Beneficial if dealing with other GST-registered businesses
• Allows claiming GST on business expenses

FILING FREQUENCIES:
• 6-monthly returns - for businesses with annual turnover under $500,000
• 2-monthly returns - for businesses with annual turnover $500,000 - $24 million
• Monthly returns - for businesses with annual turnover over $24 million

KEY OBLIGATIONS:
• Charge 15% GST on taxable supplies
• Keep tax invoices for purchases over $50
• Maintain GST records for 7 years
• File returns by due dates (5th of the month following your GST period)

IMPORTANT CONSIDERATIONS:
• Register through myIR on the IRD website
• Consider accounting software to track GST
• Seek professional advice if uncertain about registration
• Monitor turnover regularly to ensure compliance

detailed_results.query: What employment law compliance do I need for hiring my first employee?
detailed_results.response:
ESSENTIAL EMPLOYMENT LAW COMPLIANCE CHECKLIST FOR FIRST HIRE:

1. BEFORE HIRING:
   • Register as an employer with Inland Revenue (IRD)
   • Set up PAYE (Pay As You Earn) tax system
   • Set up KiwiSaver employer contributions system
   • Establish workplace safety systems (Health & Safety at Work Act)
   • Get employer liability insurance

2. EMPLOYMENT AGREEMENT REQUIREMENTS:
   • Must provide written employment agreement
   • Must include mandatory clauses:
     - Names of employer and employee
     - Job description
     - Work location and hours
     - Pay rate and frequency
     - Holiday and leave entitlements
     - Problem resolution process
   • Allow employee time to seek independent advice
   • Keep signed copy on file

3. ONGOING COMPLIANCE:
   • PAYE Returns: Submit monthly
   • File employment information within 2 working days of each payday
   • Maintain accurate holiday and leave records
   • Minimum wage compliance
   • Provide minimum leave entitlements:
     - 4 weeks annual leave
     - 11 public holidays
     - 5 days sick leave (after 6 months)
     - 3 days bereavement leave
     - Parental leave (if eligible)

4. WORKPLACE REQUIREMENTS:
   • Display health and safety information
   • Maintain accident register
   • Provide proper training and supervision
   • Have clear workplace policies
   • Equal Employment Opportunities (EEO) compliance

5. RECORD KEEPING:
   • Wage and time records
   • Leave records
   • Employee details
   • Tax declarations
   • Employment agreements
   • Training records
   • Health and safety records

IMPORTANT: Consult with employment lawyer or HR professional for specific guidance.

detailed_results.query: What are the steps to register a company in New Zealand?
detailed_results.response:
STEPS TO REGISTER A COMPANY IN NEW ZEALAND:

1. PRELIMINARY STEPS:
   • Choose and reserve a company name
   • Ensure name complies with Companies Office requirements
   • Check trademark database to avoid infringement
   • Reserve name through the Companies Office website

2. REQUIRED DOCUMENTATION:
   • Company address (registered office and address for service)
   • Director details (must have at least one director)
     - Full legal name
     - Date and place of birth
     - Residential address
   • Shareholder information
   • Tax registration numbers (IRD number)
   • Company constitution (optional but recommended)

3. REGISTRATION PROCESS:
   • Create a RealMe® account if you don't have one
   • Log into the Companies Office website
   • Complete the online registration form
   • Pay the registration fee
   • Submit required documentation

4. POST-REGISTRATION REQUIREMENTS:
   • Apply for IRD number
   • Register for GST (if expecting turnover >$60,000/year)
   • Set up PAYE if planning to hire employees
   • Open business bank account
   • Set up proper record-keeping systems

5. COMPLIANCE CONSIDERATIONS:
   • Annual return filing requirement
   • Financial statement preparation
   • Tax return obligations
   • Director duties and responsibilities
   • Record keeping requirements

IMPORTANT NOTES:
• Process typically takes 1-2 business days if all information is correct
• Registration can be done online through the Companies Office website
• Professional assistance (lawyer/accountant) is recommended but not mandatory
• Costs include name reservation and registration fees
• Consider trademark protection for your company name

RECOMMENDED NEXT STEPS:
• Visit business.govt.nz for detailed guidance
• Consult with a professional advisor if needed
• Set up compliance calendar for ongoing obligations
